response.answer_text: Yes, I have. I don't talk about it, or him, much, if at all, but it is a memory that I will probably never be able to forget, and the guilt I associate with it will likely never fade. It was a little over 10 years ago now…  The year was 2008, and I was just a 15-year old kid when it all started. My parents had divorced when I was a toddler, and my Mom, who had won custody, remarried a few years later. My childhood was largely unremarkable up to that year. My younger brother, elder sister, and I lived with our Mom and Dan in the North Houston suburb of Spring. There were some social tensions in school for all of us, as we had moved from a “poorer” district, and the other children knew it. However, there was never any “real” danger or harassment. Even still, the mild bullying I experienced, combined with my stubborn, combative nature, greatly shaped the way I would deal with problems throughout my adolescence. At first, our makeshift family got along reasonably well. It wasn't until around my Freshman year of High School that we started having serious problems in the house. It was 2007 then, and my sister was 17-years old, and she, too, had a penchant for violent problem-solving. This had, in the past, been the cause of conflict between the 3 of us kids, but especially between me and her. At this time, however, her fights were almost all with Mom, or Dan. These battles lasted for most of that year until, after one particularly explosive fight between the 3 of them, my sister packed up her belongings, what little Mom and Dan allowed her to anyway, and left to live with her then-boyfriend. This left only me and my brother, alone. Stefany leaving like that crushed Mom, too. Prior to that event, I had talked with my Dad about the possibility of moving in to live with him. We had always been close, and my relationship with Dad was much better than with Mom. After Stefany left, I decided I couldn't put Mom through that again, and I was assuring my younger brother, Trevor, that “Dan wouldn't run me out of that house like he did to Stefany.” Well, Dan overheard that remark, and, as you could probably guess, he was not pleased. That day, he took out all of his frustrations on me, but, fortunately, it did not get violent. You see, Dan towered over little 14-15 year old me. He was ~6′3″, 265 pounds, and strong. I was maybe 5′5″ and 115 pounds, and on that night he used every bit of that advantage as he bent me backwards and screamed in my face for hours while Mom just watched and drank her wine. The situation continued to escalate after that night. I started avoiding coming home after school, opting instead to stay at a friend's house as much as possible. I started carrying a pocket knife anytime I knew he wouldn't be at work, just because it gave me a (false) sense of security. That illusion was shattered a few months after my 15th birthday, when Dan decided that my insolence needed to be physically dealt with. He spent that morning just beating the hell out of me. So I too left. I called my Mom, after Dan was safely gone for work, and told her that I was moving in with Dad. The summer of 2008 were some of the best months of my life to date. My Dad bought a double-wide trailer in Tomball, so that I didn't have to transfer schools, and we lived together, just the two of us and his dog. Dad was 65 at the time; was a Vietnam vet who I respected more than anyone before or since; and was retired, so we spent the whole summer together. This was much better than the paltry 4-days per month that the Courts had awarded him after the divorce. During this time, all I ever had to worry about was football and school. I met a girl (who I later married), made friends, and truly enjoyed life. Until November 11, 2008. It's a day that I'll never forget. I didn't feel well when I woke up that morning, so I woke Dad up and asked if I could stay home from school. “Not a problem,” he said, “I'll call the school when I get up in a few hours.” So I texted my girlfriend to tell her happy birthday and explain that I wouldn't be at school, and then I went back to bed. I shot out of bed just a couple of hours later and ran to the bathroom to puke, but when I got in there, Dad was already doing the same. It was around 9AM, and I knew what I needed to do right then. You see, Dad was a Type-1 Diabetic (insulin-dependent). His getting the stomach flu could be life-threatening because it would cause his blood sugar to plummet in a way that his body couldn't regulate. Additionally, the poor circulation to his extremities, associated with his condition, made vessel constriction from dehydration a real fear. I should have stopped right at that moment and called 9-1-1, and I knew it. I knew it. My Mom had explained the dangers of him getting a stomach virus to me before, and I was taking multiple Health Science courses that explained the disease. I knew he needed medical attention before something awful happened. Every single thing I typed here went through my head when I saw him over that toilet, but I did nothing. I just puked on the floor and sulked off to my room feeling sorry for myself because “my tummy hurt.” It was 5 more hours before an ambulance was called, and only after he had collapsed on his way to the bathroom because his legs wouldn't work from lack of circulation. We got to the Emergency Room at Tomball Regional Medical Center, and they rushed him into a room. The doctors provided him with narcotics for the leg pain he was experiencing, but they missed the larger circulatory problems that were causing it. Dad developed gangrene and had both legs amputated at the VA hospital shortly after we were admitted. Still, his spirits were high, even if it was only a show for me. That is, until the infection set in. Ultimately, Dad died less than one month later on December 8, just a couple of weeks after spending his 66th birthday in a hospital bed. At that point, he was being kept alive entirely by machines. His liver had failed, the infection was spreading, and they had amputated everything up to his pelvis trying to stop it. There was nothing they could do.  My self-pity and inaction killed my own Dad, and it is something that I carry with me to this day. Yes, I know that you can twist the words to argue that I wasn't responsible for his death; many school counselors, Army chaplains, and a psychologist have all done that, but the simple fact remains that I am culpable. I knew what needed to be done to stop that from happening, and I chose not to do what I knew needed to be done. If I had called 5 hours earlier, and they got him on an IV before the tissue started to die, he might well still be alive today. But he isn't, because I didn't.

Yes, though I'm doubtful anyone on here would be inclined to believe me. I was 14 when it happened and it was a home break in. My parents left the house to go to the Casino, which is a normal thing for them about once a week. I was in my room taking a nap and I heard a noise in my parents master bedroom which was a little ways down from my room. It sounded like a door slammed shut. I grabbed a large bowie knife that I had under my bed and four shuriken, yeah I'm a nerd and I still buy these things online and yes, my parents were fine with it. I honestly didn't think anyone was actually in the house, so I casually strolled in the room and saw things thrown around, specifically a jewelery box. It didn't look normal, it didn't look like the wind blew anything. It was thrown and I heard more noises in the bathroom, which thankfully was quite large so it took the culprit time to go through. I didn't proceed any further, instead what I did was I closed the door to the master bedroom and blocked it with a chair so you couldn't open the door. I then proceeded to call the police and told them in a very calm manner that there are people in my house and they broke in and that they had weapons (they apparently didn't have any weapons but I thought it would be smarter to tell the police that so that they would rush over faster, also I didn't know at the time so it was kind of a guess.) Now, like an idiot I was talking on the phone and yelling to the bedroom “I called the police, they will be here soon!!” I thought that would deter the person that broke in. (Bad idea when you are fourteen and you still sound like a little kid…) It did not, instead the guy tried to open the door and couldn't so he took about two or three minutes bashing the door open. While he was doing that I was still on the phone with the police, or the operator actually. She was telling me to hide and not to try anything so I followed her instructions. I went in the living room and hid behind the couch. The man who broke into the house finally bashed through the door and went into the kitched and grabbed a knife and entered the living room. I was very calm until I saw him with a weapon, at fourteen that scared the hell out of me. The police still weren't close, couldn't even hear the sirens yet. The man who broke in was yelling and telling me to come out. I chose not too. Instead I stayed hidden behind the couch and watched him through a little side corner thing. I watched him go back through the kitchen and to the master bedroom. This is when it all happened…I could have left him alone and just waited for the police but instead I did something stupid. I quietly got out from behind the couch and watched him go into my parents bedroom. I snuck behind him all the way there and knifed him through the back. I did it with all my force and it ended up piercing through and through. He fell over and was trying to get up on his knees sort of, at that age I thought he was still okay and that he could still move and was going to pull a gun on me or something (keep in mind I still didn't know if he had a weapon other than the knife he took.) I ran half way into the hallway and through my shuriken at him. Two of them hit him, one in the throat and the other in the stomach region. I watched him bleed out on the floor and I remember it all pretty vividly. By the time the police arrived the guy who broke into the house had been dead for probably five or six minutes. The police were so slow, I have mad respect for them but I remember that when they arrived they took their time. They knocked on the door asked if anyone was home, etc. If I didn't kill the guy, chances are he might've found me and killed me or worse. I never tell anyone this story because no one believes it half the time, due to the shuriken being utilized, I guess. Anyway this led to years and years of councilor’s and psychiatrists, etc. Due to me taking a life at such a young age and feeling totally fine with it. I stopped with the shrinks at the age of 17 because I'm fine. I felt nothing when I killed the guy who broke in because I knew that it was him or me, that's all I've ever felt about the incident. I viewed it as evil versus good, I guess. That was my way of rationalizing what I did. To be honest, there is probably something wrong with me. Maybe something is tweaked but I'm okay with it because I know that I can excel through things like this with little to no remorse because of the way I view it in my mind. Anyway that's my story…I was going to post anonymous but whatever. Not important enough to be anonymous. Peace

My mother was diagnosed with colon cancer the summer I graduated from college. She had surgery to remove part of her colon and we were told she should receive chemotherapy just as a precaution. The surgery went well and she was home recovering and on disability from work. I, too, was still living at home, working as a high school math teacher. It quickly turned into the year from hell. As you might imagine, being a 22 year old female high school teacher is pretty terrible. Sexually harassed? Check. Mistaken for student? Check. Belittled by ancient curmudgeony coworkers? Check. Assigned a subject I was not qualified to teach? Of course! Where better to stick the new girl? My mom seemed to be doing ok at home. My retired dad would take her to all her appointments. My sister got married. I got engaged. I weaseled my way out of continuing to teach the class for which I wasn’t qualified. Things seemed to be looking up. I decided to stay at my current school for the following school year, much to the dismay of my department head who proceeded to berate me for my decision to stay on and try to improve. (My principal was actually quite supportive, however.) Then February came, and Mom got sick again. No one seemed interested in finding out what exactly was wrong. Weeks would pass between appointments where doctors would shuffle her off amongst themselves with no diagnosis. In late March, she was admitted for exploratory surgery at UPenn. After a few hours the surgical oncologist came out to tell us (my dad, my three older siblings and me) that the cancer had metastasized all over her abdominal cavity. There was nothing to do and he gave her 6–8 weeks to live. Dazed and confused we went home to prepare our childhood home for my dying mother. The hospital bed was set up in the living room, hospice nurses were scheduled, and my oldest sister and I were given our own nursing duties. She was on wound care and I was in charge of IVs. What my sister had to endure to care for my mother’s wound was nothing short of heroic. My mother’s abdomen was completely sliced open from sternum to pelvic bone. The wound was at least an inch deep. The staples they had used to close the wound had to be removed early because the hospital neglected to notice (or take seriously) that my mom was allergic to metal. All types. And adhesive. Twice a day the wound needed to be unpacked and repacked with sterile, saline soaked gauze. If any piece of it so much as breezed by my mom’s skin or the bed linens, my sister had to throw it out and start over. I had to set my mom up on IVs. She needed TPN-basically intravenous food-and all her medications through the IVs. She couldn’t digest anything by mouth. She could only consume clear liquids. The pumps, the beeping, the endless nights of no sleep wore on us all. As the weeks went by things were fairly the same until week 5, when she took a turn for the better and seemed to be improving. By week 6, the honeymoon was over and Mom took a fast turn toward death. To see her, my mom, always the strong one, always so practical and blunt, so scared and in so much pain brings tears to my eyes even now 17 years later. The shaking began. She could not stop shaking and she could no longer speak. I can still remember how she looked at us with fear, and in pain, and with pleading in her eyes. It was early Sunday morning and no one had slept. We didn’t know how to help her. By 6:00 AM we were so desperate we got a doctor friend of the family who was able to steal Ativan from his hospital so we could sedate Mom. Finally, the hospice nurses were able to get ahold of a doctor to prescribe Valium so we could give that to her to keep her unconscious. Family members were called and told it was nearing the end. All that day and the next, people came in and out of the house sharing their condolences and saying their goodbyes to her. By evening on Monday, the hospice nurses told us it was time to let Mom be alone. It was clear to them that she would not leave with us nearby. “How?” we asked. We need to give her her medications every few hours. That’s ok they said. You need to sleep they said. And they told us to give her a much larger dose of Valium than we had been giving her. My sisters and I were very wary of this. But they assured us all would be well. It was I who was in charge of all medications and injections. So I took the little bottle of Valium and filled up the syringe and pushed it into the portable catheter and into my mother’s body. We all kissed Mom and each other and went upstairs to go to bed. We would leave her to sleep alone that night. When I got to my room, my fiancé, who was and had been sleeping on the floor in my room for days, tells me he forgot his cell phone downstairs. But he is too uncomfortable to go back downstairs by himself to retrieve it. So I go back downstairs. As I approach the living room I look at my Mom in the hospital bed with tubes coming from everywhere and medical supplies and equipment and pillows and tissues all over the room. The room where I learned how to crawl as a baby and walk as a toddler. Where I would drag my legos up from the basement and create wild keg parties out of little tiny plastic blocks. Where every Christmas tree we ever had was decorated and lit and every Christmas present I had ever given or gotten was opened. And there was my mom, gone. Dead. Just like that. Not breathing, no pulse, just peace. And the realization that I had pushed the final large dose of Valium into her cancer-ridden body. And that now she was gone. And at 23, I would never have a mom again. No mom at my wedding, no grandmother for my three children. And although she was in so much pain, and it was all ugly and miserable and depressing, and that she now was definitely somewhere better, it provided no relief for me. I thought it would and it didn’t. And I had pushed the final dose. And so with that, I killed the woman who gave me life.

Unfortunately, yes. I have killed a man. My boyfriend wanted a steam cleaner, and I wanted to pick up a few things from Walmart. It was around 8 pm when I departed. Little did I know, this would be the biggest mistake of my twenty-two years of living. I arrived at Walmart, safely. I picked up the steam cleaner and a few other silly items (home decor, cleaning supplies, etc.) After checking out, I headed home. My drive went smoothly, up until I was a block away from home. It was around 9:45 pm at this time, and I was literally just thinking “I almost made it home.” I was traveling around 35–45 mph. The street lights are very dim on this road, and at night, you can rarely see what's in front of you. I see a red car parked on the opposite side of the road, but since this road is very scenic (during the day) I really didn't think much of it. That is when I heard the horrifying thud - “bdunk bdunk bdunk” and I slam on my breaks. As soon as I open the door, I hear the blood curdling screams. An African American man is running towards my SUV (which I later find out that it's his son). He rips his tank top off and starts calling me a b*tch and informs me that I just killed his dad. His brother followed. I immediately start screaming. I still couldn't see his father. I ran up to the red car, and his two sons start to hug me and inform me “ma'am, you didn't do anything wrong. There was a family altercation, and he wanted to die. We called an ambulance for him to get him some help.” I am still screaming. I come upon his body, sitting in a pool of blood. Within minutes, a police man pulls up. He immideatly starts rendering aid. Minutes later, an ambulance pulls up. I am still in shock. They started to do CPR, before putting his barely alive body in the ambulance. He was life-flighted to a local hospital. It turns out that his body was laying between two street lights, and from his chest up was laying in my lane - face down - wearing a black sweatshirt - against black pavement. He told his ex-wife who was at the scene, that he wanted to kill himself because she did not want him back. I wonder why the ex-wife wouldn't put her car in front of his body. I wonder why the two sons couldn't seem to move him from my lane. I wonder why it had to have been me. The man was pronounced dead upon arrival. I'm twenty-two years old. What could I have done that was so wrong that I deserve to live with this the rest of my life? I will never stop replaying the horrifying sound from running the man's body over, the blood-curdling shrieks, the image of the man laying in a pool of his own blood. I don't know if I will ever be able to live with myself.

Yes. My actions contributed to my father’s death. Sorry in advance for the length and my rambling. The incident happened over 20 years ago. I haven’t ever talked about it outside of my mom, counselors and a couple of close friends. I don’t think I even talked to my brother about it much. My father started to have neurological symptoms in early 30’s when I would have been a toddler. He was having trouble with balance, dizziness, voice, and hand eye coordination. He started seeing a doctor as things were getting worse. The diagnosis was Mitochondrial Myopathy. This is a rare condition that basically destroys your brainstem and eventually you loose control of your body. Picture an extremely drunk person trying to walk and communicate, that is how my father lived every day. The person ends up dying because the brain stops controlling the muscles. Its degenerative and over time it gets worse. When I was a freshman in high school my father’s illness was progressing quicker and he ended up leaving his job and going on disability. During this time my mother had to find a fulltime job to provide for the family (I also have a younger brother who was in grade school). The way things worked was my brother and I would get ready for school in the morning and leave. My mom would get my dad up, dressed, and fed and then leave for work. My brother and I would return from school and take care of him until my mom got home. Our school worked with our parents so we could leave at noon. That way my dad was not left alone for long periods of time. My dad’s condition continued to deteriorate throughout my time in high school. By the time I graduated he was confined to a wheel chair. During my summer break my freshman year I was working in the garage and my dad was out there with me. At this time, I was frustrated with the situation our family was in. It was hard to be that young and have your parent dependent on you. We were arguing quite a bit during this period. Thinking back, I feel very guilty of the way I acted towards him. I should have been more patient and understanding. Anyway, as we were out in the garage working, we started to argue. I ended walking away to finish doing something. My dad wanted to watch. I didn’t want to take the time to move him in his wheel chair, so he tried to move himself. He ended up flipping backwards and hitting his head on the concrete. It was the worst sound I have ever heard in my life so far. I ran over to him and got him back in his chair and inside. I told my mom what happened, and we took him to the hospital. My father never made it out of the hospital. His condition worsened. He couldn’t recognize us and started to hallucinate. He needed to have an operation to relieve pressure in his skull. His brain was swelling, and he ended up in a coma. He was in the hospital for 3 months before the doctor said he was never going to be able to breath on his own. My mom took him off life support and he died a couple of hours later. I blamed myself for his premature death. If I would have just moved him a few feet, the accident would had never happened. I took a semester off school. My mom did not take my father’s death well. And I believe she did hold some resentment towards me for what happened. Since the accident I have had my share of problems, drinking, drugs, and self-harm. I have many scars on my body from stupid things I have done because of the guilt. I ended up going to a counselor. I had numerous hospital visits and a finally a doctor intervention lead to me getting help. I am doing better now. I still see a counselor, I have quit drinking and hurting myself. I still have times where I am overcome with guilt and depression. I don’t think I will ever fully be able to let that go. Thanks for reading and letting me put this out there.

I was 7 years old when I killed a man. I am going anonymous for this for obvious reasons. I was in Primary school at the time. A small school, located in the nasty part of the city. Regardless of this, I enjoyed the school. Children were nice to eachother, and I loved going to that school. We even had a school sleepover there one day. There were 2 play areas, one being smaller for younger children, and a seperate bigger one for older kids. The big one consisted of a big field, a little further behind the football area and the average play areas with benches and toys scattered around. The school was well monitored with teachers at lunch and break time, but kids were trusted as the school had a good reputation. Before any comments come, this is not the teachers fault. The teachers were on regular duty. It was a simple accident in the hands of a young child. So towards the back of the play area where the field was, there was a little shed. The shed was on top of a slope like hill, where my friends and I would run around. The shed was never used for anything other than storing equipment for the school. It was quite a large playground for a small school. Anyway, the top of that hill was my favourite spot. We would hide behind the shed and play games. The shed and field were located to the left corner, where there were houses seperated by the average metal fencing. Cut to the story, it was a regular day for me, hanging out on top of the hill behind the shed. One day, I thought it would be fun to throw rocks down, and see which one went the furthest to the bottom of the hill. I would throw rocks, one after the other, until the next period, being physical ed. All the children in my class and myself occupied the other side of the field to play football that day. Here I am minding my own business and messing about with the grass or my shoes or whatever a child would be doing to pass time, waiting for the teams to be picked. Suddenly the head teacher arrives, occupied by 5 or 6 other teachers. They calmly take me to the office. My mother was already there, and a few police men taking statements. They sat me down to discuss the situation, and locked the door. Soon after I found out that one of the rocks I threw went over the fence, and into the back yard of an elderly couple. Coincidentally, it hit the old man in the neck, which caused him to fall to the ground. After this, his wife found him unconcious and he was rushed to the hospital. Yes. It wasn’t intentional, but it was ironic. Escrow had just closed on a building I had bought to house my business. It was in Bell Gardens, CA. About a year later, I think, a young woman pushing a baby stroller was hit and thrown about 50 feet. I think both she and her baby were killed. The family of the man I had hit hired a couple of lawyers. Of course, my insurance company got one for me. Actually, they didn’t get a lawyer FOR me; they got it to protect the money they would have to pay if the man’s family won. If I was helped collaterally, they didn’t object. The matter went to trial. By the time the man’s family’s lawyers got through describing me, I felt around for my devil’s horns and pointy tail. They said that the man was just getting his life back together, that he was a “shade-tree” mechanic with his father, and had four or five kids who would need to be cared for. They wanted my insurance company to pay for their upkeep until they were OUT of college, including Mercedes automobiles to go back and forth. They lost the case. One of the witnesses to the accident testified that he was right behind me and that I could have done nothing to avoid the accident. I’m glad he was there. The lawyers were a couple of those low-life types that brag that if they didn’t win, the client didn’t have to pay. Still, somehow, I was found to be “partly” responsible. At least one of the jurors felt that way, anyhow, so a little of the insurance money went the family —- and probably all of it to the lawyers. I was advised to go to a psychologist. She was a very attractive lady. After 20 minutes, she said to me, “You’re fine; what do you want to do with the rest of your hour?” No, I didn’t suggest that she join me on the couch; I just wanted to leave and forget about the whole thing. But do you know what? You never forget.

Despite an interest in palliative care, I am not a proponent of euthanasia. I regard that as a failure which good practice should have avoided. But there was a time when I had no other choice. I was working on a surgical unit where the professor was more politician than clinician & thought that the only criterion worthy of promotion was machismo. A good trainee, he said, must be “decisive & consistent”. This encouraged excessive bravado & knife-happiness in the service as everyone tried to impress the prof with overly heroic surgery. My immediate superior was trying to corner the market for oesophageal cancer surgery. One day we were referred a 70-year old man with a cancer obstructing the middle third of his oesophagus. The surgeon decided to remove it through a combined approach. The top end would be detached via an incision in the neck, then through an abdominal incision the oesophagus would be drawn down & detached from the stomach. Finally the transverse colon would be isolated, drawn up into the chest & used as an interposition graft. Things went wrong in the anaesthetic room. The anaesthetist wanted to use a device called a Robertshaw endobronchial tube (Robertshaw Tube | Wood Library-Museum) to ventilate the patient on one lung while the neck incision was open, as it would breach the pleural cavity & collapse that lung. He could not get the tube in. He sent for a bronchoscope & saw that there was tumour in the tracheal bifurcation & realised the diagnosis was wrong. He told the surgeon that this wasn’t oesophageal cancer, it was lung cancer invading the oesophagus, it would be inoperable & the operation should be cancelled. At this point the total wrongness of professorial policy showed itself. The surgeon knew that admitting the error & cancelling the op would be seen by the professor as indecision & inconsistency, & promotion prospects would wither. In a masterpiece of retrograde logic he answered, “Nonsense, we have decided to do oesophagectomy, therefore it is oesophageal cancer, and surgery is still needed for palliation.” Surgery yes, but that particular surgery, no. The correct procedure was to insert an oesophageal stent, but he went ahead with the planned heroic procedure. It was brutal. Normally in an abdomino-cervical excision the oesophagus is fairly easily drawn down into the abdomen, but this one was anchored by the tumour & removing it took half an hour of blind, blunt dissection through the mediastinum (the wall of tissue between the lungs & tiger country with all the big vessels going to & from the heart). As a final insult the colon graft looked to have a very dodgy blood supply at the top end when we’d finished. Now it fell to the anaesthetist to try &salvage the situation. He whipped the patient off to ITU & anticipating that the patient would not breathe unaided for 10 days or more had a tracheotomy performed for long term intubation. Well first the top end of the graft became infected. We were in with a chance of fixing that with right antibiotics. A week passed & the patient was holding his own. He still had the trachy but was fully awake & breathing through it without assistance. That was Friday & I went off duty feeling he might make it. There was a nagging feeling though, that it was only a matter of time before the tumour invaded the graft & blocked that too. So I clocked on early on Monday & checked him out. The infection seemed to be under control but the ITU nurse reported blood in the aspirates from the tracheostomy. I suggested they tell the anaesthetist as it probably meant the tube had been in too long so it was time to remove it & let the tracheostomy close. 15 minute later, on the way to my normal operating session I was crash-paged back to ITU. When I got there a fountain of blood was spraying out out the tracheostomy in a display that would do justice to one of the Alien movies. I realised instantly that the residual tumour in the trachea must have eroded into a major blood vessel, almost certainly a pulmonary vein, & half the patient’s cardiac output was exiting the tracheostomy with each heart beat. My houseman [intern] arrived shortly after, took one look, said “Oh my God”, then keeled over himself. I saw the terror in the patient’s eyes, pleading for help, & know I could nothing for him. Well maybe one thing. That is the one & only time I ever administered a lethal dose of morphine. I probably shortened the patient’s life by all of 10 minutes, but at least I couldn’t see the fear in those eyes any more.

After filling out the police reports, railroad incident reports, and etc, we were relieved by another train crew and sent home by crew van. It was a very sad experience. The second accident was at a major highway crossing where the man driving a Dodge pick up ignored the crossing warning devices and drove directly across the tracks in front of the train, because he was using his mobile phone while driving, this time the vehicle was not ejected from the tracks, and instead became entangled with the front end of the locomotive and was dragged 1/4 of a mile down the track while the emergency brakes were stopping the train. The 911 radio calls were made, and we attempted life saving measures on the victim, but he had already expired. The destroyed truck was so badly entangled to the train that the tow truck could not free it from the front of the locomotive. I instructed the tow truck driver to attach a heavy duty chain from the truck’s frame to the rail, and then proceeded to back the locomotive away from the truck so it could be towed off the tracks and the victim removed to the waiting ambulance. There were three of us on the crew, Engineer, Conductor and Brakeman, and the rest of the trip was pretty much spent in silence instead of the usual in cab conversations. These types of accidents happen all the time on railroad grade crossings all over the country. Trains can’t stop quickly, physics comes into play when all that mass is moving at speed, and even with emergency brakes applied, it takes a considerable amount of time and distance to stop a fully loaded moving train. So for everyone choosing to read this answer, please take just a little extra time when driving a vehicle and approaching any railroad crossing, and look and listen for trains at crossings, even if the crossing warning devices like gates and lights are not activated. I ran a block, walked a block and jogged the last two blocks. I get to the payphone and I realize I have no money. So I walk into the Stop n’ Go and say, “There is a man outside of our apartment, beating on the door and threatening to kill me and my mother and sister. I jumped off of our second-floor balcony and ran a half-mile to get here, but I have no money to call the police, may I please use a quarter?” The clerk—not looking up at me—says, “It’s free to call 911.” — “Oh, OKAY.” (Why am I in here talking to this moron then???) So I call 911 and I say, “There is a man outside of our apartment, beating on the door and threatening to kill me and my mother and sister. I jumped off of our second-floor balcony and ran a half-mile to get here because we have no phone in our house, can you please send the police?” The operator asks, “So your house is at the STOP N’ GO?” “No, I just ran up here. We live in the So-and-So apartment complex at this-and-that address. He’s outside of there right now! Please send the police!” So the operator says, “The police will be there in a couple of minutes.” Relieved, I walk back home at a leisurely pace. I’m imagining being on the news and being hailed as a hero: “HERO KID HOPS 2ND FLOOR BALCONY, DASHES HALF MILE TO ALERT COPS OF NEIGHBORHOOD DIRTBAG. KID RECEIVES KEY TO THE CITY—AND A HOME PHONE. FOR LIFE.” (I really hated not having a home phone all of the time.) I get a little less than a block from my house and I’m looking for police lights or listening for a shootout or something when I see a figure moving in the darkness. It gets closer and I see it’s my mother. she has a weird smile on her face and she zooms past me. There is another figure coming towards me and it’s Red and He has a Weird smile on his face too. He runs past me. The first thing that pops in my head is that they have reconciled, come to get me, and I’ve called the police for nothing. I could just picture the New Headlines: “IDIOT KID BREAKS BALCONY, HARRASSES CONVENIENCE STORE ATTENDANT AND FILES FALSE POLICE REPORT. RECEIVES LIFE SENTENCE. AND ELECTRIC CHAIR.” But when I turned around to see what was going on, I was speechless… So when I initially jumped off the balcony and ran off into the darkness, Red gets it in his head to jump up the balcony. My mother goes to the balcony door—thinking it’s me—and sees Red. She immediately opens the front door and runs out of the house. Maybe it’s a predatory thing, but Red, now inside the house he’s been trying to get into for the better part of an hour, decides to chase after my mother. My mother told me later that she was just going to run all the way to the Stop n’ Go because she figured that’s where the police would be, but since she saw me, she thought maybe the police were with me. That’s why she stopped. She shouldn’t have done that, because Red ran right up to her and slugged her in the eye… I turn around and all I see is Red, Bobbing and Weaving, trying to punch my mother like a professional boxer. In my head, I feel like this is a movie: Any instant, the police will come rushing in and tackle Red. Maybe put their knees in his back and pull him up by his handcuffed wrists. But this was NO movie. All I hear is my mother whimpering and him grunting, “yeah, yeah, yeah,” like he was defeating Muhammad Ali. I stood there for the longest second of my life, PRAYING the police were milliseconds away from bursting on the scene, while sticking my hand into my pocket. I pulled my hand out and looked at it. The Butterfly knife was already open. My mind races: “AM I READY TO DO THIS??? Is this what my life is now? Don’t I love Red? Even though he’s abusive? Sometimes, he’s abusive. Mostly, he’s a good guy. My mother loves him. He’s funny and generous when he wants to be. Why does he have to hit women? Speaking of women: What if he punches her too hard? The police will be too late. He’ll run like last time and get away with it. LIKE LAST TIME. I’ll just stab him once and Then he’ll go back to Chicago…” It’s funny how your body changes for expectations. I’ve playfully fought all my life and have never hit anybody to bruise them. So I’ve always punched slow, maybe at half speed. and not very hard. just hard enough to make that punching sound. That Hollow, “Whumpf” that sounds like someone kicking a box. But when I decided to put this knife into Red, all I ever saw was the handle sticking out of him. I can’t remember cocking back or ever swinging at him. First, it was in his upper back and I tried to pull it out, but it felt stuck, so I yanked it out as hard as I could. He stiffened up and then I saw the knife in the middle of his back, but this time it was easier to pull out since I knew how much force to use. Again it was in his upper back and I picked him up and slammed him to the ground. I pulled the knife out again and then it was in his shoulder. then it was in his arm. He turned over to face me, but I was not looking at him. Not his face anyway: I was looking at the spots this knife was appearing on his body. When I found the knife plunged into his forehead, just above his eye socket, I thought, “He’s dead now, might as well finish it…” You know how you hear about someone being stabbed so many times and you wonder, “What kind of a maniac does that?” The answer is: Anybody. It becomes mechanically rhythmic and you don’t notice how many times you do it. It happens so fast. SO. FAST. My mother says that it happened so quickly that by the time she opened her eyes from his last hit, he was already on the ground and I was stabbing him in the head. I was completely out of it, because I wasn’t thinking about anything until I accidentally cut my mother on her arm when I was taking another swing. I snapped back and got up. My mother was screaming, “I Hate YOU! I HATE YOU!” To Red while he was laying there motionless and staring at the sky. Half Staring. One eye was pretty messed up. I was trying to calm my mother down, telling her, “Ma, leave him alone. He’s not listening to you right now. Calm down.” But she wouldn’t calm down. She was holding her arm (where I accidentally cut her) and yelling at Red. A man and his wife and daughter came out of their house to see what the commotion was. I’m standing there, holding this knife, and I say, “This is the kind of stuff I get into at 3 o’ clock in the morning???” Trying to make a joke. They quickly go back into their home and I survey the scene: The grass is wet with blood, The sidewalk has blood splatter all over it and glance down at myself. My hand and the knife has a small amount of blood on it, but my shirt looks like I just played five rounds of paint ball. I had blood all on my shirt and on my face (my mom says) and some lady—Out Jogging—just comes up to us and demands to know what is going on. I tell the lady the whole story and she says, “It’s 4 in the morning, you’re a black man, covered in blood. Standing over another black man, covered in blood. You need to flee. You can’t explain your way out of this, Honey. You have got to run. Hide that knife and get out of here!” I give my mother the knife and I take off. I tell my mother I’m going to Renee’s house because I didn’t know she had anything to do with the situation. I run that whole mile to her house (well jogged and walked) and I rang her bell. She sees me and she says, “So you actually did it?” I just nodded and walked into her house. She asked where my mother was and I told her. She left and I went into B’s room (He was there for the weekend) and I tried waking him up. “Hey, B. B! I just killed Red, man I need to talk!” Non-committed, he grumbled, “Tell me about that shit when I wake up.” I go into the kitchen to wash my hands and think about how great it Would’ve been to go to heaven, since now I’m going to spend eternity in damnation because this guy wanted to beat on my mom. It wasn’t fair. It Was NOT FAIR. I WAS NEVER GONNA GET TO VOTE. I sat down and started watching Cartoons. A half an hour later, there was a knock at the door. “I’m not answering that.” I knew it couldn’t be anybody for me, so I wasn’t going anywhere NEAR that door… But the door unlocked and the goddamn Police walked in! Behind them were Renee and My mother… So I went to jail. but Red aint die then, so I got Aggravated assault, but he only had one good eye left and he died later. It would’ve been self-defense but because I stabbed him too many times while he was down and trying to defend himself I got Aggravated Assault. No Trial, I plead no contest and received probation. All because I was a minor and they changed the rule to try children as adults in violent crimes the year AFTER I did what I did. but I got kicked out of Texas all the same. Thanks for reading this!

What’s It Like to Kill Someone? Ok this is from someone from the internet that I just read a few days ago so better to just share it in here. This is from a soldier of war. Enjoy reading. by Travis Switalski, Sr. I have been asked that question more times than I care to count. I have been asked it by complete strangers, friends, and by those closest to me. I have been witness to the anger that erupts when someone is asked it and I have on occasion been the outlet of that anger. Most real honest-to-God combat veterans will tell you that asking that question is inappropriate, to say the least. However, the farther away I get from my time in the military, the less the question bothers me. In fact, I often find myself asking “what was it like to kill someone?” When I think of being asked it occurs to me that I was offended by it not because it was inappropriate, but because I didn’t really have an answer to the question. It was much easier to explode into a tirade or ignore the question than to face it.  War veterans detail what it is REALLY like to kill someone in emotional video | Daily Mail Online The act of killing I think is immensely private. My buddies saw me do it, but the feelings I had about it were mine alone. Those feelings are not always the same for everybody. I felt a sense of relief and a feeling of accomplishment. I had done it without hesitation and without fanfare. Others took it much harder outwardly. It was not uncommon for guys to lose their nerve after taking a life, or for them to become overwhelmed with the feeling that they had done something wrong. Then, some of the boys took great pleasure in killing, or at least they seemed to. As a defense against labeling the act of killing as killing we use gentle euphemisms to describe it like wasted, smoked or zapped. We also dehumanized our enemy to make wasting him easier on the conscience by calling him Haji, The Dirty Haj, and Raghead to name a few. And after the first time I killed another human being came as a relief to me, all of the ones I killed after him didn’t matter. Killing became a perfunctory and mechanical aspect of my employment. What is it like to kill someone? As I look back on it now, years after what I hope is the last time I will ever have to kill another person my answer is this: The act of killing is a terrible and sad thing. For many it is a mentally and spiritually damaging act from which they’ll never recover. For others it doesn’t mean anything. For me, all I know is that it is better to be alive than to be dead, to walk the Earth, not to walk in someone else’s memories. I also know that to explain what killing is “like” to a person who has never had to kill, is an exercise in futility. They possess an annoying curiosity on the subject of killing, and maybe they have a right to know exactly what we did on their dime and in their name. Perhaps instead of coming unglued or shutting down, we as veterans should tell them exactly what they want to know even if they could never possibly understand it. Maybe we should find a way to articulate it to them in one word. If I had to sum killing up in one word, I’d say, “Easy.” Read more to his experiences: What’s It Like to Kill Someone? | Military Experience & The Arts And once again, this answer was from someone or from some website I have read a long time ago. So sharing it all with you might give you some thoughts and ideas based of his experiences in life as a marine.

I guess you could say so. Let me explain. My grandmother was in her mid-80s doing very well (very smart, walked 3 miles a day, etc.) when she had a cancerous lump grow on the side of her throat, under her ear. She went through two years of chemo and radiation. To treat where they did required removal of her teeth (she had years before capped all her teeth) and insertion of a feeding tube. She wasted away to nearly nothing and expressed many times she was ready to go but my mom, who was an only child, would not hear of it. Eventually we noticed she would have difficulty getting around and become very confused. Testing showed that the tumor was now in her brain. She lost consciousness. Doctors offered my mom the option to do surgery as a last resort but I was able to convince her to not do surgery, just let her be comfortable. They gave us a nice private room and my mom and I stayed with her around the clock until she breathed her last. They had her on morphine and I confess at any sign of her discomfort we gave her a hit. She passed peacefully with us both holding her hands and my mom telling a story. I would not have it any other way! I contrast this with my husband’s grandmother whose children stood around her hospital bed, crying, doing the rosary, and listening to his grandmother’s moans and cries of pain that we younger folks could hear down the hall — for hours. We asked if they would give her something for pain and were told it was available but they wanted her conscious for as long as possible. They selfishly let her suffer! If I could have lessened her pain I would have happily done so and I deep down hope those who selfishly let her suffer eventually find out what that was like. In my view, if they had things to say to her, they had plenty of time to say them before her final hours when she was in such pain.

A woman presumed to be a drug overdose was brought into the Emergency Department. Report given stated that patient was found unresponsive, shallow respirations, breathing eight times a minute. After being given Narcan, an Opiate Antidote, the patient had shown signs of reversal with improvement in respiratory status, though she still had not regained consciousness. The physician ordered another dose of Narcan intravenously. Narcan is a drug I had administered many times in my career as an Emergency Room Nurse. I gave the ordered dose without any reservations, especially since she had received a dose en route that improved her condition without any complications. Upon administration, the patient sat straight up, terrified, and said, “What did you just do to me?” Then she collapsed back onto the bed in full cardiac arrest. Death is a rare side affect of Narcan administration.[1] We attempted to resuscitate her but it was in vain. She died as a result of the medication sending her into acute narcotic withdrawal. Never in a million years did I foresee her dying. In nursing school we are taught that the possibility of accidentally causing a death exists. One just assumes that it will not happen to them. Since that night, I have never taken a medication for granted again. The event was investigated by a Root Cause Analysis committee (standard procedure) and I was cleared of any wrongdoing. The physician was also cleared in the same investigation. Being cleared of wrongdoing offers little comfort to the person who pushed the drug that caused her death. Going back to work and giving medications again has been the hardest part. It gives one a new respect for medications as well as life. Not in the sense you probably mean. But I define murder to include "knowingly allowing others to die when you could have stopped it without any survival risk to yourself." In that sense, I'm a serial killer. Every winter, in my city, homeless people die of exposure. I could save at least one every year. There's an unused, spare bedroom in my apartment. I choose to allow people to die rather than invite them to stay in it. UPDATE: The comments make me feel that my answer was too terse—that I didn’t add enough detail to make my position clear. So.. — You’ll put yourself and your family at risk if you let homeless people stay in your house. Possibly. I certainly wouldn’t do it without an extreme amount of background checking and recommendations. My point is, even if I was 100% certain that a homeless person would cause no threat at all, I wouldn’t let him stay. If it was my a neighbor of mine who I’d known for 25 years, and he just became homeless, I wouldn’t let him stay. But we can eliminate homeless people and spare rooms altogether. I probably shouldn’t have used them as the only example in my answer. Every year, many people die of malaria. Far fewer would die if they had access to quality mosquito nets. There are charities that provide them. Each net saves lives. If there are 10,000 nets, more lives will be saved than if there are 9,999. If I spend some of my money on just one net, I will save at least one life. If I don’t spend that money, someone will die who could otherwise have been saved. I can afford to pay for a net. — So why don’t you do it? Because I’m selfish. That was the point I was trying to make in my answer. If you always do what you believe is right, you’re a much better person than I am. — You can’t save the world! Even if you let a homeless person stay with you, there are lots of other homeless people. Are you going to let all of them stay with you? How can you possibly afford to buy mosquito nets for everyone who needs them? I have no interest in saving the world. It’s not something I ever think about. I don’t believe I’m ethically obligated to save the world, because I don’t believe I’m ethically obligated to do things that are impossible. A hundred-thousand people working together can’t save the world; one person certainly can’t. What I can do is increase (or decrease) the net amount of happiness in the world. If I make just one person happier, the world is better. If I don’t, it’s not better (by that net amount of happiness). — If you spend all your money on mosquito nets, you’ll be unhappy. True. But I wasn’t advocating spending all my money. A lot of research shows that, once someone is safely above the poverty line, additional wealth isn’t likely to increase his happiness. That’s been true in my life. When I was younger, I earned five-times less than I earn now. And yet I’m not five times (or even two times) happier now. In lots of ways, I’m less happy, because I now have more stuff that I’m constantly worrying about protecting and losing. Being a homeowner has added anxiety to my life that I never had when I lived in apartments. If I spent half—or even a fourth—of my salary on helping other people, I’d almost certainly be just as happy as I am now. I might be more happy, because giving often has that effect. And others would be happier. I could increase the amount of happiness in the world, but I choose not to. — What’s with this obsession with happiness? There are other things that are more important! Not according to my ethics. I’m a Consequentialist (Utilitarian). Ethical systems are either consequentialist or deontological. Deontological systems are based on rules: “Don’t kill; don’t steal; don’t lie; etc.” And they tend to care about one’s intentions. Consequentialist systems care about (guess what?) consequences. And most are based around a single goal: minimizing the net amount of suffering in the world and maximizing the net amount of happiness. That’s the entirety of my ethical system. If I do what I can to maximize happiness, I’m a good person; if I don’t, I’m not. Everyone’s happiness has equal weight, including my own, which is why I shouldn’t give away all my money. It’s why I shouldn’t become homeless myself, so that my entire house can be a used as a shelter for others. — Why be a consequentialist? That’s simply how my mind works. I didn’t read a book and get convinced by arguments. Consequentialism just seems to be my instinctual ethical system. It was my system before I knew the name for it. Later, I read some books, and they filled in some blanks for me. But, as far as I can tell, it’s just in my nature to be a consequentialist and, like most modern consequentialists, to have an ethical system based around minimizing suffering and maximizing happiness. — Consequentialism is flawed, because … Maybe. All ethical systems are flawed. I like to discuss ethics, so please feel free to ask a question about consequentialism. Let me know about it, and if I can answer the question, I will. But a full-blown discussion about consequentialism is beyond the scope of this thread. Flawed or not, it’s my system. — Okay, but that doesn’t mean you’re a murderer! Allowing someone to die who might otherwise live is not the same as killing someone. If your ethical system is centered around consequences, it is the same. According to my system of ethics, there’s no difference between me pushing a child into a lake and me refusing to save a drowning child that someone else pushed into the lake. Either way, the child dies. Either way, that’s the consequence. The only difference would be if, by saving him, I put myself at risk. If he dies and I die, there will be a lot more suffering in the world than if just he dies. But if I can save him without risk, I need to do so. Otherwise, I’m as bad as the guy who pushed him. If you disagree with that, you’re not a consequentialist. Which is fine, but I am. This ethical issue is often explored via the Trolly Problem: a trolly with broken breaks is racing towards three people, who are standing on the tracks. If it hits them, they will die, and you’re too far away to be heard if you yell. But you’re near a switch. If you pull it, you will divert the trolly to another track, saving the three people. Unfortunately, there’s one guy standing on that track. If you pull the switch, the trolly will hit him and he’ll die. If you do nothing, the three people on the other track will die. Many deontologists would choose to do nothing. Many consequentialists would throw the switch. (A lot of people are caught in-between. They have an impulse to throw the switch and another impulse to not throw it. They view the Trolly Problem as an unsolvable ethical paradox. It’s fairly common for people to have both deontological and consequentialist instincts, even if they conflict with one another. Most people aren’t entirely consistent.) There are all sorts of complications. What if the one guy is a dangerous psychopath and the three others are doctors who save thousands of lives every year? Or the other way around? If you’re interested in discussing that, you should probably start another question. — Stop beating yourself up. Get therapy! I don’t beat myself up. I rarely think about this stuff. I have a really busy life. The question was “Have you ever killed a human being?” I simply answered it, giving my ethics and understanding. — Well, if you truly believe you’re a murderer and you don’t do anything about it—or even think about it all that often—you’re a bad person! You’re bad by your own definition! Yes. — Well, then: why don’t you do something about it? Because I’m weak and selfish. Maybe one day I’ll be a better person.

I have not killed anyone through direct action that I know of but have spent time in environs where life was very cheap. I have compassion. I don’t hunt. I don’t wish ill on others. I don’t support war as a threat. I don’t support the death penalty. I hope to have a long life shared with people I care for and hope they have long happy lives as well. I share their concerns and guilt when confronted with death. I am aware of my mortality and empathize with that awareness in other humans. Heck, I have sympathy for elephants rummaging through the bones of their families although what their motivation is cannot be entirely known to me. The thread of continuity in the answers here is profound concern and guilt. One life lesson to me is that life really is cheap. We humans are replaceable even in the most horrible conditions and we are so good at replication that we are crowding ourselves out of existence. The miracle of life is at best a misnomer. In a crowded world a more likely miracle would be to prevent life from exceeding its capacity to sustain itself. That is not a final solution endorsement. It is an acceptance that if we spent nearly the resources we spend on sustaining life and fending off death on preventing life from overwhelming us in the future then our planet and thus our species survival would be more secure. All our fears and guilt over the sanctity of life are conventions that we impose on ourselves, albeit with the best intentions. I certainly don’t want a murderous psychopath anywhere near me or mine but the presence of one doesn’t really affect the balance. I will be replaced, my children and loved ones will be replaced if not by murder or accident then by the vagaries of illness or growing old. Civilizations seem to build cathedrals of sanctity around life. It serves the commendable function of giving us common cause to not beat each other to death with clubs or ICBMs. The more developed, the more we remove ourselves from the other half of the life / death equation. That’s a weakness. It makes us less. We deny a truth, we spend inordinate human, social, manufacturing, economic and moral capital on denial of an imperative. We recoil from activities that increase the likelihood of death, some which improve the condition of civilization like exploration and development in hostile locations. We handcuff ourselves. It’s going to happen. Regardless our best efforts to mitigate and relieve, to tell ourselves that we are “doing something” the results are undeniable. Tie score. Life 100%-Death 100%.

Yes. It was the evening of 21st November 2009. I was jumping with my trophy around the house! I had won it for a young writer competition that day which was held at an interschool level.Although I had already started writing short stories and poems at online sites under the pen name : Vani ..this was still very special for me..because this was going to earn me recognition!! I was super excited and was waiting for my father to return from work! He is a heart specialist at a renowned hospital in delhi. As soon as I saw his car drive into the driveway..I rushed to greet him at the door. He handed me his bag ,loosened his neck tie..and went to sit on the sofa. My younger brother Akshay brought him water and my mother brought tea with biscuits. He had just sipped the tea when he saw me all jumpy and asked me “why do you look so happy?” To which my face lit up.I showed him the trophy and gave him my biggest smile!! He examined the trophy..and asked “ what did you get it for?” “For the young writer competition!!” I replied beaming with joy.… “I secured the first position papa and a small contract in which my next 10 poems and short stories would be published in a popular youth magazing! And tomorrow we have to go to Rohini to make my registration. I mean wow papa!! I am so excited !! I have even decided the pen name..that I would use to write my stories : Vani!! And dad..” but my dad cut me short. “Malika I will eat early today..ok ..Akshay get my bag in the room..” He started taking off his shoes. He got up from the sofa and started heading towards his room. I looked surprisingly towards my mom and then my brother Akshay ..he simply gave a shrug. I called after my father ,holding my trophy in my hand “ papa ..did you like it?” He simply replied with a “hmm” without even looking back. My mom was setting the table and my brother Akshay was busy reading the medical thriller “SHOCK”by Robin Cook. The table was set. The smell of chilly paneer had filled the room. My mom had cooked it specially for me as a treat for my winning the contest. My dad came out of the room in his white kurta pajama and sat down on the dining table. We were all eating when my dad suddenly spoke up “what are your plans Ira..how is your preparation going for your 10 board examinations?” I answered in a casual way “arrey papa..abhi toh bohot time hai boards mein..but padai chal rahi hai achhchi”( oh dad..there is lot of time in examinations ..but yeah..studies are going on at good pace) He stopped eating and looked at me,“what is this casual attitude Ira ? I expect better from a student like you.” “Sorry papa ..I didn't..”but I was cut short… “I don’t want your sorry.. I want atleast 97%in your board examinations ..do you get it?Because only then will you be able to get the science stream and become a doctor like me.” my dad replied in his heavy voice. I looked at my mother and blinked my nervousness at her. She looked at me and gave me the, dont-look-at-me-i-told-you,look. I mustered all my courage and spoke up “Papa ..I don't want to become a doctor.. I want to be a writer and a full time blogger..Infact I have already started writing at the online platform under the pen name Vani..and you know..” but again I was cut short by my father. “ I think if you specialise in cardiology..it would be great. I would love to hear ‘Heart specialist Vikrant Mehrotra’s daughter Ira Mehrotra is a cardiologist’..it indeed would be music to ears..what do you say Malika?” My mother simply nodded without looking up from eating. But I couldnt take it anymore “papa are you even listening to me..I want to be a writer” He went on with his eating without saying a word. I was almost in tears when I said “papa at least hear me out..please” To which he simply said “I heard you alright Ira but I choose to ignore the unimportant things.” Tears started rolling down my cheeks. “But papa..” “Ira no more discussions … I want the best for you..I want to see you successful” He got up and went off to wash his hands. I left my plate and went running inside my room.I fell asleep on my bed crying. The next morning I got up early and rushed out of my room. I sighed a breath of relief when I saw my father sitting on the dining table with his morning newspaper. I went up to him and said “papa..today we need to go and register at Rohini..” He looked up at me and gave me stern look..which mean “no means no”. He folded the newspaper,picked up his coat ,gave my mom a good bye peck on her cheek and left. That was it. I got a call from the Young writers office and they asked me if I was coming to Rohini or not and of course I refused saying that it would take a toll on my academics. …… I kept crying unconsolably. My mother tried to console me by making my favourite breakfast of coffee and homemade pancakes. I was still crying when I opened my science book to study (I didn't go to school that day). Just then the photo frame above my desk caught my eye ,it was a photo of my dad holding me up in his arms when I won the first prize in a fancy dress competiton ,in which I had dressed up as a … “doctor”. I realized he looked so proud just to see me dressed up as a doctor! I smiled,brushed off my tears and started studying. I clearly remember.. that evening I sat down on my laptop and deleted all my accounts from online writing portals. I took out all my writing pads,took down my poems from my bulletin boards,put them in my grandma's trunk ,locked it and carried it to the attic. I kept the trunk in one corner and closed the attic door behind me. That day I killed Vani…a writer. I had to kill her to give birth to Dr. Ira Mehrotra. Today I am a practising ‘heart’ specialist. I still laugh at the irony though.. my father is a heart specialist who failed to understand my heart. With love Arundhati Singh Deb
